<br>
Several people have pointed out what you should do and gave you excellent links &amp; quotes about landlord responsibilities.<br>
<br>
Send the registered return receipt letter now, detailing all the fixes you want.  Include pictures if possible.  Keep copies of those pics and your letter.  Do not expect a rapid response.<br>
INCLUDE in your letter your plans to purchase a replacement door &amp; deadbolt lockset &amp; to deduct it (including installation costs) from your next month's rent if the repairs aren't made w/in 10 days.  Request all responses to your letter be made in writing.<br>
<br>
From what you've described, you apartment sounds like it was built very cheaply, and I'd surmise the owner is looking for maximum profit, not concerned much about having happy tenants.  He may ignore your letter completely, or just eventually give you a cheapo lock to replace yours.  Maintenance guys will probably just adjust your door a bit to make it lock a bit for a few days, and then you'll have the problem over again. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Go to a Home Depot or Lowe's or a locksmith's store TODAY and go buy one of those bar-things you can use to brace your door to lock it from the inside securely even without a normal lock on the door.  You need a locked door now, not tomorrow, not next week, or whenever the apartment complex maintenance crew finally shows up.<br>
<br>
(btw, buy a steel door, not a wooden one!)<br>
<br>
